Thanks! You’re right that if a predicted probability is extremely close to 1, it’s effectively fixed—but my method doesn’t hard-lock past predictions.

In your example, even if sequence 1 was initially assigned class 1, when I get to sequence 50 I recompute the best joint assignment for sequences 1–50 from scratch, under the no-repeat constraint, by maximizing the sum of log-probabilities. That means sequence 1 can be reassigned if it improves the overall joint likelihood, which can free up class 1 for sequence 50 if that’s the better global choice.

So early mistakes don’t necessarily propagate: at each step, I re-optimize the joint assignment for all sequences seen so far. This outperforms per-sample argmax on the set {1…50} as a whole. Ultimately, I only predict sequence 50 at that step, but I can still improve its accuracy.


